---
import StickySidebarLayout from "../layouts/StickySidebarLayout.astro";
import LinkButton from "../components/LinkButton.astro";

import "../styles/global.css";
---

<StickySidebarLayout title="Sticky Sidebar Layout Example">
  <div slot="photoheader">
    <h1>image</h1>
  </div>
  <div slot="main">
    <h1>Article Title</h1>
    <p>
      This is an example of how to use the Sticky Sidebar layout. The sidebar
      will remain visible as you scroll through this content.
    </p>

    <h2>Introduction</h2>
    <p>
      This layout is perfect for articles, documentation, or any content that
      benefits from persistent sidebar navigation or information.
    </p>
    <p>
      The sidebar uses <code>position: sticky</code> to remain in view while the
      main content scrolls naturally.
    </p>

    <h2>Features</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Responsive design that stacks on mobile</li>
      <li>Sticky positioning that works across browsers</li>
      <li>Customizable content slots</li>
      <li>Clean, minimal styling</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Usage</h2>
    <p>
      Simply import the StickySidebarLayout component and use the "main" and
      "sidebar" slots to add your content.
    </p>
    <p>
      The layout automatically handles the responsive behavior and sticky
      positioning.
    </p>

    <h2>Customization</h2>
    <p>
      The layout uses CSS custom properties and can be easily customized by
      overriding the styles.
    </p>
    <p>
      The pink background and border styling are just examples - change them to
      match your design system.
    </p>

    <h2>More Content</h2>
    <p>
      Keep scrolling to see how the sidebar stays in position while this content
      flows naturally.
    </p>
    <p>
      This makes it perfect for table of contents, author information, related
      links, or any persistent navigation.
    </p>
  </div>
